Scottish independent schools maintain a curriculum of academic excellence and this is continued in 2018 with another series of outstanding results at the exams, strengthened by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other collective efforts.
With over 30,000 students all over Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further higher education, their chosen career and their place in the world as global citizens.
As a field of education capable of developing and adopting a personalized school curriculum, we note that modern languages continue to be a popular subject and demand within schools.
Nelson Mandela said: "If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message will reach his brain.
If you speak him in his mother tongue, the message will reach the heart."
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely on English only if we want to create trust relations with people from other countries.
From the results of this year's exams, we can see that languages are above the graduates, with the highest rates of success within independent schools.
68% of students who have studied foreign languages have obtained the maximum number of votes.
The data, collected from the 74 schools members of the SCIS, showed that 72% of the students received the highest vote with praise in Chinese, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish received the highest vote.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are promoting foreign languages as basic skills for children and young people, who will undoubtedly need them in the future.
Currently, languages, as a matter choice, are considered at the same level of STEM materials (science, technology, technology and mathematics) in the study plans of independent institutions and elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the United Kingdom Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 found that the reasons for the difficulty of covering jobs are attributable in 17% of cases to a lack of language skills.
That is why language skills are becoming increasingly essential to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more opportunities for work requiring language knowledge, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the chosen career, if you have learned a second language, you will have an effective advantage in the future with a life skills like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically lead a multilingual person to competition.
In a survey of YouTube among over 4,000 adults in the United Kingdom in 2013, 75% was unable to speak a foreign language at a sufficient level to maintain a conversation and the French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is so important for today's children.
The knowledge of more languages, in particular those of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding a valid job.
In Scotland, each school will differ in the languages taught.
Various schools will focus on the more traditional modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered the most important for the United Kingdom by looking at 2020, such as Mandarin Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever your son's interest, there will always be different languages to choose from in independent schools, with the specialized teaching staff in this area.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and provide them with the necessary skills for success, whatever their future.
It is not possible to deny at this time, in a global trading system, that languages continue to be fundamental to the future of the country, and this must be reflected in teaching.
