HIV/AIDS: China reports an increase of 14% of new cases
China has announced a 14% increase in the number of people affected by HIV and AIDS.
Over 820,000 people are affected by these diseases, according to health authorities.
About 40,000 new cases have been reported already in the second quarter of 2018.
The vast majority of new cases are due to sexual transmission, which marks a change from the past.
In some regions of China, HIV has been spread in the past as a result of infectious blood transfusions.
But the number of people who have contracted HIV in this way has declined to almost zero, according to the Chinese health authorities at a conference in Yunnan province.
Year after year, however, the number of people affected by HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000 units.
The transmission of HIV by sex is an urgent problem in the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was criminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is still widespread.
Because of the country's traditional values, some studies estimated that 70-90% of men who have sexual relations with other men eventually marry women.
Many of the transmissions of diseases are caused by inadequate protection during sexual relations within such relations.
In 2003, the Chinese government promised universal access to anti-HIV drugs as part of its commitment to managing the problem.
